text: Why does looking and red and white blood cells under the microscope make me nauseous. There’s literally no reason for this

Leanna VanVoorst, medical technologist, is using a hematology analyzer to count red and white blood cells. Before hematology analyzers were widely used, Leanna says she counted blood cells manually, looking at a blood smear on a slide under a microscope. pic.twitter.com/8IofI4sBHj

It’s blood under a microscope. The white bits are white blood cells and the bits that look like cars are actually red blood cells.

This is my own blood under the microscope! Cool, right? Those pink cells that look like donuts are red blood cells, the big purple cell is a white blood cell, a lymphocyte to be exact, and those small purple fragments are platelets. pic.twitter.com/7UYJbCbGaR

COMMON CELL TYPES in one microscope field that a Lab Scientist encounters when performing a manual count of White Blood Cells (WBCs). Neutrophils- Band and Segmented, Monocyte, Eosinophil, Basophils, and Nucleated Red Blood Cell. The only cell missing is a Lymphocyte. pic.twitter.com/3kKdP7GifP
Under the microscope, white blood cells and red blood cell cookies! # labweekgoodiespic.twitter.com/gEl3T6oSBm
This is what leukaemia looks like in red and white blood cells under a microscope pic.twitter.com/ZyP2zUUzZN

So I had my blood taken and put under a microscope ...firstly it’s amazing to see all your red blood cells alive and moving but I was laughing my ass off when this white blood cell showed up....its a for real snapshot! Cheers Jon x pic.twitter.com/Tf1rdb8fv5
